    "solution": "<p>Let</p>\n<p>$$ K=\\sin\\left(\\frac{\\pi}{18}\\right)\\sin\\left(\\frac{5\\pi}{18}\\right)\\sin\\left(\\frac{7\\pi}{18}\\right) $$</p>\n<p>We need to find</p>\n<p>$$ \\sin\\left(\\frac{10K\\pi}{3}\\right) $$</p>\n<p>First, write the angles in degrees:</p>\n<p>$$ \\frac{\\pi}{18}=10^\\circ,\\qquad \\frac{5\\pi}{18}=50^\\circ,\\qquad \\frac{7\\pi}{18}=70^\\circ $$</p>\n<p>So,</p>\n<p>$$ K=\\sin 10^\\circ \\sin 50^\\circ \\sin 70^\\circ $$</p>\n<p>Now use the standard identity:</p>\n<p>$$ \\sin 3x = 4\\sin x \\sin(60^\\circ+x)\\sin(60^\\circ-x) $$</p>\n<p>Taking $x=10^\\circ$,</p>\n<p>$$ \\sin 30^\\circ = 4\\sin 10^\\circ \\sin 70^\\circ \\sin 50^\\circ $$</p>\n<p>Since</p>\n<p>$$ \\sin 30^\\circ=\\frac12 $$</p>\n<p>we get</p>\n<p>$$ \\frac12 = 4\\sin 10^\\circ \\sin 50^\\circ \\sin 70^\\circ $$</p>\n<p>Hence,</p>\n<p>$$ \\sin 10^\\circ \\sin 50^\\circ \\sin 70^\\circ = \\frac{1}{8} $$</p>\n<p>Therefore,</p>\n<p>$$ K=\\frac18 $$</p>\n<p>Now substitute in the required expression:</p>\n<p>$$ \\sin\\left(\\frac{10K\\pi}{3}\\right) = \\sin\\left(\\frac{10}{3}\\cdot\\frac18\\pi\\right) = \\sin\\left(\\frac{10\\pi}{24}\\right) = \\sin\\left(\\frac{5\\pi}{12}\\right) $$</p>\n<p>Now,</p>\n<p>$$ \\frac{5\\pi}{12}=75^\\circ $$</p>\n<p>So,</p>\n<p>$$ \\sin 75^\\circ=\\sin(45^\\circ+30^\\circ) $$</p>\n<p>Using the formula $\\sin(A+B)$:</p>\n<p>$$ \\sin 75^\\circ=\\sin 45^\\circ \\cos 30^\\circ+\\cos 45^\\circ \\sin 30^\\circ $$</p>\n<p>$$ =\\frac{1}{\\sqrt2}\\cdot\\frac{\\sqrt3}{2}+\\frac{1}{\\sqrt2}\\cdot\\frac12 $$</p>\n<p>$$ =\\frac{\\sqrt3+1}{2\\sqrt2} $$</p>\n<p>So the value is</p>\n<p>$$ \\boxed{\\frac{\\sqrt3+1}{2\\sqrt2}} $$</p>\n<p>Hence, the correct option is A.</p>",
